                    // /*Parte de document querySelector en ingles*/ 
                    document.querySelector("#first-quote").innerHTML ="What is depression?";
                    document.querySelector("#second-quote").innerHTML ="Everyone feels sad or down from time to time, but these feelings usually go away in a short time. Depression, also called clinical depression or major depressive disorder, is different. Depression can cause serious symptoms that affect how you feel, think, and coordinate daily activities like sleeping, eating, or working. It is a disease that can affect anyone, regardless of age, race, income, culture, or educational level. There is research suggesting that genetic, biological, environmental, and psychological factors play a role in depression.";
                    document.querySelector("#tree-quote").innerHTML ="Depression can co-occur with other mental disorders and other illnesses such as diabetes, cancer, heart disease, and chronic pain. Depression can make these health problems worse, and vice versa. Medications taken for these illnesses sometimes cause side effects that contribute to symptoms of depression.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema1").innerHTML ="What are the different types of depression?";
                    document.querySelector("#problema2").innerHTML ="Two of the common types of depression are:";
                    document.querySelector("#li1").innerHTML ="Major depression, which involves symptoms of depression most of the time for at least two weeks. These symptoms interfere with the ability to work, sleep, study, and eat.";
                    document.querySelector("#li2").innerHTML ="Persistent depressive disorder (dysthymia), which often includes less severe depressive symptoms that last much longer, usually for at least 2 years.";
                    document.querySelector("#li3").innerHTML ="Other forms of depression include the following:";
                    document.querySelector("#li4").innerHTML ="Perinatal depression, which occurs when a woman suffers from major depression during pregnancy or after childbirth (postpartum depression).";
                    document.querySelector("#li5").innerHTML ="Seasonal affective disorder, which comes and goes with the seasons of the year, usually starting in late fall or early winter and going away in spring and summer.";
                    document.querySelector("#li6").innerHTML ="Depression with symptoms of psychosis, which is a severe form of depression in which a person also shows symptoms of psychosis, such as having fixed and disturbing false beliefs (delusions) or hearing or seeing things that others cannot hear or see (hallucinations).";
                    document.querySelector("#li7").innerHTML ="People with a diagnosis of bipolar disorder (previously called manic depression or manic-depressive illness) also suffer from depression.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema3").innerHTML ="What are the signs and symptoms of depression?";
                    document.querySelector("#problema4").innerHTML ="Common symptoms of depression include the following:";
                    document.querySelector("#li8").innerHTML ="Persistent feelings of sadness, anxiety, or emptiness";
                    document.querySelector("#li9").innerHTML ="Feelings of hopelessness or pessimism;";
                    document.querySelector("#li10").innerHTML ="Feelings of irritability, frustration, or restlessness;";
                    document.querySelector("#li11").innerHTML ="Feelings of guilt, worthlessness, or helplessness;";
                    document.querySelector("#li12").innerHTML ="Los of interest or pleasure in activities and hobbies;";
                    document.querySelector("#li13").innerHTML ="Fatigue, decreased energy, or feeling slowed down;";
                    document.querySelector("#li14").innerHTML ="Trouble concentrating, remembering, or making decisions;";
                    document.querySelector("#li15").innerHTML ="Trouble sleeping, waking up early in the morning, or sleeping too much;";
                    document.querySelector("#li16").innerHTML ="Unplanned changes in appetite or weight;";
                    document.querySelector("#li17").innerHTML ="Aches and pains, headache, cramps, or digestive problems with no apparent physical cause, or that are not relieved or treated;";
                    document.querySelector("#li18").innerHTML ="Suicide attempts or thoughts about death or suicide.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema5").innerHTML ="How is depression diagnosed?";
                    document.querySelector("#problema6").innerHTML ="To be diagnosed with depression, a person must have five symptoms of the illness every day, most of the day, for at least two weeks. One of the symptoms must be a depressed mood or loss of interest or pleasure in almost all activities. Children and teens may be cranky instead of sad.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema7").innerHTML ="If you think you may have depression, talk to your health care provider. Primary care doctors routinely diagnose and treat depression and refer people to mental health professionals, such as psychologists or psychiatrists.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema8").innerHTML ="During your visit, your doctor or other health care provider may ask when your symptoms started, how long they last, how often they occur, and if they don't allow you to go out or do your usual activities. It may be helpful to take notes about your symptoms before your visit. Some medications and certain conditions, such as a virus or a thyroid disorder, can cause the same symptoms of depression. Your health care provider can rule out these possibilities by performing a physical exam and interview, and ordering lab tests.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema9").innerHTML ="Causes";
                    document.querySelector("#problema10").innerHTML ="The exact cause of depression is unknown. As with many mental disorders, it can be made up of a variety of factors, such as:";
                    document.querySelector("#problema11").innerHTML ="Biological differences. People with depression have physical changes in the brain. The significance of these changes is still uncertain, but over time they can help identify causes.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema12").innerHTML ="Brain chemistry. Neurotransmitters are chemicals found naturally in the brain that likely play a role in depression. Recent research indicates that changes in the function and effect of these neurotransmitters, and how they interact with neurocircuitry involved in maintaining mood stability, may play an important role in depression and its treatment.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema13").innerHTML ="Hormones changes in the body's hormonal balance may play a role in causing or triggering depression. Hormonal changes can occur during pregnancy and in the weeks or months after delivery (postpartum), and from thyroid problems, menopause, or other conditions.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema14").innerHTML ="Hereditary traits Depression is more common in people whose blood relatives also have this disorder. Researchers are looking for genes that may be involved in causing depression.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema15").innerHTML ="Is depression the same in all people?";
                    document.querySelector("#problema16").innerHTML ="Depression can affect people in different ways, depending on their age.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema17").innerHTML ="Children with depression may be anxious, moody, pretend to be sick, refuse to go to school, cling to their parents, or worry that one of their parents will die.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema18").innerHTML ="Older children and teens with depression may have problems in school or low self-esteem or may be quiet, easily frustrated, or restless. They may also have symptoms of other disorders, such as anxiety and eating disorders, attention deficit hyperactivity disorder, or drug use. Older children and adolescents are more likely to have excessive sleepiness (called hypersomnia) and increased appetite (called hyperphagia). In adolescence, girls begin to have depression more often than boys. This may be due to biological, hormonal and life cycle factors that are unique to women.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema19").innerHTML ="Young adults with depression are more likely to be irritable, complain of weight gain, and hypersomnia, as well as have a negative outlook on life and the future. These people often have other disorders, such as generalized anxiety, social phobia, panic disorder, and drug use.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema20").innerHTML ="Middle-aged adults with depression experience more depressive episodes, their libido is reduced, they have insomnia in the middle of the night or they wake up in the early morning. They may also mention more frequently that they have gastrointestinal symptoms, such as diarrhea or constipation.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema21").innerHTML ="Older adults with depression often experience sadness or grief, or they may have less obvious symptoms. They may report feeling a lack of emotion, rather than a depressed mood. Also, older people are more likely to have other health conditions or pain that can cause or contribute to depression. In severe cases, memory and reasoning problems (called pseudodementia) may be noticeable.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema22").innerHTML ="How is depression treated?";
                    document.querySelector("#problema23").innerHTML ="Treatment of depression usually includes medication, psychotherapy, or both. If these treatments don't lessen symptoms, another treatment option may be brain stimulation therapy. In milder cases of depression, treatment may begin with psychotherapy alone, with medication added if the person continues to have symptoms. For moderate to severe depression, many mental health professionals recommend a combination of medication and therapy early in treatment.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema24").innerHTML ="Selection of the appropriate treatment plan should be based on the individual's health condition and needs, and under the care of a health care provider. It may be necessary to try different things in order to find the treatment that works best for you.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema25").innerHTML ="Medicines";
                    document.querySelector("#problema26").innerHTML ="Antidepressants are medications that are often used to treat depression. It takes some time for them to work, usually 4 to 8 weeks, and symptoms such as trouble sleeping, eating, or concentrating often improve before mood improves. It's important to give medications a chance before deciding if they work or not.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema27").innerHTML ="Important: Be aware that some people, especially children, adolescents, and young adults, may have increased suicidal thoughts or behavior when taking antidepressants, especially in the first few weeks after starting or when doses are changed. Any patient taking antidepressants should be closely monitored, especially during the first few weeks of treatment.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema28").innerHTML ="Depression is said to be treatment resistant when a person does not get better after trying at least two antidepressants. Esketamine is a newer drug approved by the FDA for treatment-resistant depression and is given as a nasal spray in a doctor's office, clinic, or hospital. This medicine is often fast-acting, usually within a few hours, to relieve symptoms of depression. People usually continue to take an oral antidepressant to maintain the improvement they have made.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema29").innerHTML ="Another option for treatment-resistant depression is to add a different type of medication that may make the antidepressant more effective, such as an antipsychotic or antiseizure medication, or bupropion, an antidepressant that works differently from most medications";
                    document.querySelector("#problema30").innerHTML ="Medications prescribed by your health care provider for depression may have side effects, but they may lessen over time. Talk to your doctor about any side effects you're having. Do not stop taking medications without the help of a health care provider. If you stop taking your medication abruptly, you may have withdrawal symptoms.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema31").innerHTML ="Psychotherapy";
                    document.querySelector("#problema32").innerHTML ="Psychotherapy (also called talk therapy or counseling) teaches people with depression new ways of thinking and behaving, and also helps change habits that contribute to depression. In most cases, psychotherapy sessions are conducted by a licensed and trained mental health professional, either individually or with others in a group setting. Two of the effective psychotherapies for treating depression are cognitive behavioral therapy and interpersonal therapy. The limited use of older forms of psychotherapy, such as dynamic therapy, may also help some people with depression.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema33").innerHTML ="With cognitive behavioral therapy, people can learn to challenge and change unhelpful patterns of thinking and behaving in order to improve their feelings of depression and anxiety. Recent advances in this type of therapy include the introduction of contemplative principles and the development of specialized forms of therapy aimed at treating specific symptoms, such as insomnia.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema34").innerHTML ="Interpersonal therapy focuses on interpersonal and life events that have some impact on mood and vice versa. The purpose of this therapy is to help people improve their communication skills in their relationships, establish support networks, and set realistic expectations to help them cope with crises or other problems that can contribute to or worsen depression.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema35").innerHTML ="How can I take care of myself?";
                    document.querySelector("#problema36").innerHTML ="Once you start treatment, you should start to feel better little by little. Don't push yourself too hard during this time. Try to do things that you used to enjoy. Even if you don't feel like doing them, they can improve your mood. Other things that can help you are:";
                    document.querySelector("#li188").innerHTML ="Try to do some physical activity. Just 30 minutes of walking a day can improve your mood.";
                    document.querySelector("#li19").innerHTML ="Try to keep a regular time for going to bed and getting up.";
                    document.querySelector("#li20").innerHTML ="Eat healthy foods regularly.";
                    document.querySelector("#li21").innerHTML ="Do what you can and how you can. Decide what you must do and what you can postpone.";
                    document.querySelector("#li22").innerHTML ="Try to interact with other people and talk to people you trust about how you feel.";
                    document.querySelector("#li23").innerHTML ="Postpone important life decisions until you feel better.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema37").innerHTML ="How can I help a loved one who is depressed?";
                    document.querySelector("#problema38").innerHTML ="If you know someone with depression, help them see a health care provider or mental health professional. You can also:";
                    document.querySelector("#li24").innerHTML ="Offer support, understanding and encouragement, and be patient.";
                    document.querySelector("#li25").innerHTML ="Invite him to go for a walk, walk or participate in other activities.";
                    document.querySelector("#li26").innerHTML ="Help you follow your treatment plan, such as setting reminders to take prescribed medications.";
                    document.querySelector("#li27").innerHTML ="Make sure you have transportation to your psychotherapy appointments.";
                    document.querySelector("#li28").innerHTML ="Remind her that depression will go away with time and treatment.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema39").innerHTML ="Important: Take comments about suicide seriously and report them to your loved one's health care provider or therapist. If you are in immediate danger or thinking about harming yourself, call emergency services at 911 or go to the nearest hospital emergency room.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema40").innerHTML ="Dynamics to overcome depression";
                    document.querySelector("#problema40").innerHTML ="Dynamics to overcome depression";
                    document.querySelector("#problema41").innerHTML ="Get out of bed, when it comes to improving depression it is vitally important to stay active, although in depression it is difficult to face day to day, the simple fact of getting out of bed and facing daily activities will make you feel more trained, competent and will improve your mood.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema42").innerHTML ="Do activities that satisfied you before your depression. One of the symptoms of depression is anhedonia, that is, the inability to fully enjoy activities, which leads the person to inactivity and feedback depression, therefore doing pleasant activities will help you improve and achieve a certain satisfaction and improve your mood. You can also add new tasks that you could carry out alone or accompanied and that you have been leaving due to lack of time, laziness or other causes.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema43").innerHTML ="Do physical exercise, you don't have to do physical exercise as if you were an elite athlete, do exercise according to your physical possibilities (walking, swimming, maintenance gymnastics, pilates, yoga...). When we play sports, we secrete endorphins, a substance that positively influences mood, relaxes, favors night rest and you will feel more vital.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema44").innerHTML ="Break with the routine. If our life is routine, it is possible that this could lead us to lose motivation when it comes to doing things, as we said before that doing activities is very beneficial for depression, changing our usual routine could also be. Try to change the way you do your work, try to meet new people, change your route when going home and coming back.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema45").innerHTML ="Do activities in nature. Choose activities that are to your liking, walking in the mountains, swimming in the sea, walking in the woods... Observing the landscape, the animals, the flowers, the sunset, will not only help you relax but also make you aware of the pleasant things that life offers us.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema46").innerHTML ="Take care of your physical appearance: The assessment we have of our image is an important pillar in our self-esteem. Feeling good about our appearance improves our mood. Stay neat, wear clothes you like, take care of your image, but don't get obsessed with it.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema47").innerHTML ="Take care of your diet. It is important that you maintain stable meal times and that you have a balanced diet. In depression many times you lose your appetite and not eating will not exactly help you feel good. On other occasions, there is an increase in appetite, which makes the person eat uncontrollably, leading to a feeling of inability to control impulses that does not help to improve depression either.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema48").innerHTML ="Improve your sleep pattern. It is possible that if you are depressed, your sleep pattern has deteriorated and you have trouble falling asleep or wake up in the middle of the night. To improve your sleep, avoid heavy dinners, ventilate the room and maintain a comfortable temperature. Before going to bed you can do simple relaxation exercises to help you fall asleep.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema49").innerHTML ="Expand your circle of friends. Many people with depression isolate themselves from others either because they don't feel like interacting with others or because they think they will be a burden to others. Nothing could be further from the truth, the people who love us care about us and will do their best to help. Try to meet friends, even widen your circle of friends, being with other people will help you bond with them and enjoy their company.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema50").innerHTML ="Reserve time for yourself. In our daily life we ​​barely have time to do things for ourselves, our responsibilities and obligations consume almost all of our time. Try to find some time to be able to dedicate it to yourself every day, whether it is to take a relaxing bath, read something you like, go for a walk, or whatever else you like.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema51").innerHTML ="Be tolerant with yourself. You have to keep in mind that feeling depressed is not your fault, so you should not condemn yourself for it. Focus your attention on the achievements you are making on a day-to-day basis and reward yourself for it.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema52").innerHTML ="Objectively analyze the problems. In depression many times you lose perspective on things and you tend to see everything much more negative than it really is. Analyze the problems as objectively as you can, if you think you have lost perspective, consult someone close to you who can give you another point of view. If the problem you are analyzing has no solution, you will have to learn to live with it and accept it as a harsh reality that you have to live with. If it has a solution, write all the alternatives you have with the advantages and disadvantages of each of them, once Once this is done, start the one that is most beneficial.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema53").innerHTML ="Express your emotions. Emotions are part of our human nature and help us interpret situations. Feeling rage, anger, sadness, enthusiasm, impatience etc, is completely normal and therefore communicating them is part of managing them.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema54").innerHTML ="Don't give in to self-pity. Possibly you are at a time when you do not stop turning your head wondering why this happens to you. With this, the only thing you get is to feed back your depression generating more negative thoughts and pessimistic predictions about the future, which will make you have less and less perception of control over the situation.";
                    document.querySelector("#problema55").innerHTML ="Do not consume drugs that the doctor has not prescribed for you, medication is a very widespread resource to overcome depressive states, however, as with any type of drug, these must be taken under prescription and medical monitoring. So it is not a good idea to take medication that someone who is not an expert assures you that it is going well.";
    
